<span id="freeTextContainer15615703882160097506">I enjoyed this so much more than I could have anticipated. But I don&apos;t really feel like reviewing it in a thoughtful way. My apologies. I have always loved the correspondence technique for storytelling. It allows for digressions and timeline manipulations you can&apos;t get away with in a regular narrative. I liked the &quot;parables&quot;. A person probably gets more from the book on a subsequent reading or with more time to devote to really contemplating the parables. Fantastic. Looking forward to reading mo</span>
  <span id="freeText15615703882160097506" style="display:none">I enjoyed this so much more than I could have anticipated. But I don't really feel like reviewing it in a thoughtful way. My apologies. I have always loved the correspondence technique for storytelling. It allows for digressions and timeline manipulations you can't get away with in a regular narrative. I liked the "parables". A person probably gets more from the book on a subsequent reading or with more time to devote to really contemplating the parables. Fantastic. Looking forward to reading more Montesquieu another time.</span>
