              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1180891850459704518"> Boring... Maybe reading it in original didn&apos;t help either. Most of what was written is so long outdated, that in order for it to have been interesting, the form and the literary qualities should have been of a much greater value then they are. I guess it&apos;s a matter of taste, I don&apos;t find letter-novels very appealing. And sometimes I had a hard time finding the connection between the letters - it&apos;s not like a book that goes from a beginning to an end, it&apos;s just a collection of facts and view of </span>
  <span id="freeText1180891850459704518" style="display:none"> Boring... Maybe reading it in original didn't help either. Most of what was written is so long outdated, that in order for it to have been interesting, the form and the literary qualities should have been of a much greater value then they are. I guess it's a matter of taste, I don't find letter-novels very appealing. And sometimes I had a hard time finding the connection between the letters - it's not like a book that goes from a beginning to an end, it's just a collection of facts and view of facts... <br /> I guess this is a book to be read by people that are passionate about that period of French history, therefore being familiar with the political, economical and social context of the time. Everything (ok, almost everything) in this book is a reference to an event or to a person or to a rumor or to some plot that was fashionable at the time, so for someone unfamiliar with all that... it's just mumble bumble.. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1180891850459704518" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

