<div id="review_2108254691" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2108254691" />
    <a title="Xander" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60074558-xander"><img alt="Xander" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1490713726p2/60074558.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2108254691?book_show_action=true">Sep 07, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Xander" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Xander" href="/user/show/60074558-xander">Xander</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780192806352" href="/book/show/3077124-persian-letters">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2108254691" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14754806437825754714">Persian Letters is a novel in which Montesquieu (first edition was published anonymously in Amsterdam) gives a scathing review of France in the period 1710-1720. He does this by offering readers a rich collection of letters, supposedly written by two Persians visiting Europe.<br/><br/>Because of the foreign origin of the main characters (Usbek and Rica), Montesquieu is able to make (contemporary) readers see French society in a new light. At first, both travellers are amazed by these strange customs - wom</span>
  <span id="freeText14754806437825754714" style="display:none">Persian Letters is a novel in which Montesquieu (first edition was published anonymously in Amsterdam) gives a scathing review of France in the period 1710-1720. He does this by offering readers a rich collection of letters, supposedly written by two Persians visiting Europe.<br /><br />Because of the foreign origin of the main characters (Usbek and Rica), Montesquieu is able to make (contemporary) readers see French society in a new light. At first, both travellers are amazed by these strange customs - women not locked up in seraglios, a central government that is (relatively speaking) not led autocratically by a despot, the advancement of science, etc. It is this cultural strangeness that brings the message across that everything we take for granted, is only taken for granted because these are customs. In a sense, Montesquieu could well be called the first cultural relativist.<br /><br />But this relativism is only superficial: beneath the text lie deep criticisms of French society. The authoritarian influence of religion (especially Jesuits), ridiculous clothes fashions, the failures of John Law's banking system. The way Montesquieu is able - through the words of the ironic Rica - to ridicule these customs is magnificent.<br /><br />One of the impressing points about this book is that a 21st century reader can get a glimpse of French society during the early decades of the 18th century. And because of the constant comparison between Oriental (Persian, Turkish) and Occidental (French) cultural habits, a reader gets a good perspective on how things went in both types of society. <br /><br />One final point I'd like to stress is that Persian Letters (for me) is an implicit critique of the islamic practice of harems, eunuchs and seraglios. Even though, according to Montesquieu, the relative freedom of women in France has its downsides - like women using intrigues to dominate politics and ruling their families - this is much better than the perpetually collecting and locking up of women in Persian and Turkish societies. Slavery, concubinage and strange notions of family honor have been part of the islamic religion since its conception. I think Montesquieu does a good job of conveying to readers the ridiculousness of these practices.<br /> <br />I can't really say anything more on this book: it is too wide in scope and too varied in topics for that. I can only recommend it to people who are interested in critical thinking and the history of ideas. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14754806437825754714" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

